    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-04-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-04-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="142"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d142">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.24/185</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Chief of the
                        Division of Near Eastern Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Alling</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-04-14">April 14,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Saleh telephoned from New York to say that he had received a telegram from
                    the Minister of Finance reading as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Please insist that wheat be shipped to Iran with the greatest
                            rapidity.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I told Mr. Saleh that we were going into the whole question of supplies for Iran,
                    and we hoped that a satisfactory solution could be found in the very near
                    future. He volunteered the idea that it would be well for our Legation at Tehran
                    to concert with the Iranian Government <pb facs="0136" n="124" xml:id="pg_124"/>
                    authorities and with the British authorities in arranging a supply program. I
                    told him I was very glad to have this suggestion and that we would look into
                    it.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
